Prion diseases are fatal neurodegenerative infectious disorders that can manifest as sporadic, inherited, or acquired forms. They are also known as transmissible spongiform encephalopathies, which include Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD), Gerstmann-Straussler-Scheinker syndrome, kuru, fatal familial insomnia, and variant CJD in humans, scrapie in sheep, and bovine spongiform encephalopathy in cattle. Prion diseases originate from the accumulation of an abnormally folded isoform of the cellular prion protein (PrPc),
